Virtual Node — the concept
The problem it solves
In a standard GNN, information travels one hop per layer. Two atoms 13 bonds apart (median in your data) need 13 layers to communicate. With 10 layers, they never interact — the GNN is effectively blind to long-range structure.

What a virtual node is
A virtual node (VN) is a fake extra node added to every graph that is connected by an edge to every real node. It acts as a global message board.


Before VN:                   After VN:

   A — B — C — D               A — B — C — D
                                 ↘   ↓   ↓  ↙
                                    VN
                                 ↗   ↑   ↑  ↖
                                (connected to all)
With the virtual node present, any two real nodes are at most 2 hops apart — through the VN — regardless of the molecule's actual diameter. A 3-layer GNN on a molecule with a VN has an effective receptive field of the entire graph.

How information flows each layer

Layer l:

  1. Every real node sends its embedding to VN
         vnode ← MLP( sum_all_nodes(h) + vnode_prev )

  2. VN broadcasts its updated embedding back to every node
         h_v  ←  h_v  +  vnode

  3. Normal message passing runs on the real edges
         h_v' ←  RGCN( h_v, neighbours )
Step 2 is what was missing in the original codebase — the VN was being updated (step 1) but never broadcast back (step 2), making it completely inert.

Intuition with a molecule example
Say you have a drug molecule where a functional group on one end affects a ring system on the other end, 14 bonds away. With a 10-layer plain GNN:

Layer 10 still can't connect atoms 14 hops apart
The ring never "knows" about the functional group
With VN:

Layer 1: functional group embeds into VN (global summary)
Layer 2: VN broadcasts global summary to ring atoms
The ring now has information from the functional group
Why your results are mixed
Model	chemhiv AUC	chempcba AUC
10-layer deep GIN	0.576	  0.497
10-layer VN	      0.558  	0.541
chempcba improved (+4.3%) — it has many parallel assays where global molecular properties matter, which VN captures well.

chemhiv dropped (−1.8%) — HIV inhibition can depend on local structural features (specific binding pockets, chirality). The VN averages all atoms into one global vector, which can wash out the fine-grained local signal the plain GNN was picking up.

This is the known VN tradeoff: it improves global-property tasks but can hurt tasks that rely on local substructure — the global averaging creates an over-smoothing effect at the graph level.